Question: How do you believe ACME should better support organizations and cultural leaders?

Response ID: resp_820
Response Text: The newer rubric excludes a history of production as a parameter.  I always felt this was important.  It's wonderful that the barrier to entry for new producers is so low in Austin - it helps folks get started.  But it used to be that the longer you continued to provide quality programming, you could grow as an organization.  That is no longer the case.  Another problem is a complete lack of nuance in understanding diversity (many racially diverse organizations were denied funding or had their funding cut this year, not to mention previous years).  Before the new programs you had to be 51% or more ONE SPECIFIC non-white race in makeup, or you weren't considered diverse.  Now, arbitrary decisions from frequently uninformed or personally-conflicted panelists get to decide which organizations are diverse.  For example, 49% of my company is white, 25% African-American, 25% Latinx, and 1% mixed race - but we were not considered "diverse" enough to qualify for funding.  Other companies that also have long histories of prioritizing racial diversity were not funded or had their funding cut.  And yet we see companies that have historically been very homogeneously white in their makeup, granted funding as they make a sudden pivot to finally include more BIPOC artists.  Another problem with the City of Austin's definition of diversity is that it largely excludes queer and disabled artists, and completely excludes organizations focused on women.  An example of this is when the city cut arts funding for organizations that were BIPOC by 18-20%, but cut organizations that identified as queer or disabled by 48%.  The math shows that these types of diversity are not valued by the City of Austin.

